          "id": 2,
          "type": "image",
          "variant": "text_aside",
          "style": {
            "background_type": "COLOR",
            "background_color": "#1c1c1c",
            "card_mode": "WHITE",
            "image_size": "medium",
            "image_opacity": "0.1",
            "image_opacity_color": "#000000",
            "zoom_on_click": false,
            "attached_to_next": false,
            "padding_top": 5,
            "padding_bottom": 5,
            "custom_padding_top": 5,
            "custom_padding_bottom": 5,
            "entrance_animation": true
          },
          "image_role": "content",
          "media": {
            "path": "resources/images/orw-1.jpg",
            "alt": "ORW 1.png",
            "source_asset": "ORW 1.jpg",
            "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
            "bytes": 231822,
            "dimensions": {
              "width": 911,
              "height": 717,
              "originalWidth": 1280,
              "originalHeight": 720
            }
          },
          "body_html": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 1.8rem\">The rapid evolution of artificial intelligence compute continues to accelerate at an exponential pace. </span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.8rem\">To ensure your facility infrastructure remains highly scalable, engineers must design frames capable of surviving the next wave of macro technical shifts.</span></p><p></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "type": "text",
          "variant": "paragraph",
          "style": {
            "background_type": "COLOR",
            "background_color": "#1c1c1c",
            "attached_to_next": false,
            "padding_top": 3,
            "padding_bottom": 3
          },
          "body_html": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 1.8rem\">Click on &nbsp;each card to explore the upcoming infrastructure trends pushing the Open Rack Wide architecture to its design limits.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 4,
          "type": "flashcards",
          "variant": "flashcard",
          "style": {
            "background_type": "COLOR",
            "background_color": "#1c1c1c",
            "attached_to_next": false,
            "padding_top": 3,
            "padding_bottom": 3,
            "flashcard_size": "large"
          },
          "cards": [
            {
              "front": {
                "description_html": "<p>The Transition to Direct Current and Higher Voltages Within LVDC</p>",
                "media": {
                  "path": "resources/images/mountains.jpg",
                  "alt": "mountains.jpg",
                  "source_asset": "mountains.jpg",
                  "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
                  "bytes": 160141,
                  "dimensions": {
                    "originalWidth": 1680,
                    "originalHeight": 1120
                  }
                },
                "type": "description"
              },
              "back": {
                "description_html": "<p style=\"text-align: center\">As power density demands skyrocket toward hundreds of kilowatts per enclosure, traditional low voltage delivery paths hit a severe physical and efficiency wall. The community is actively exploring a massive architecture shift toward higher operating voltage thresholds, which dramatically reduces raw copper cable volume requirements and mitigates severe electrical line drops across the busbar grid.</p>",
                "media": {
                  "path": "resources/images/mountains.jpg",
                  "alt": "mountains.jpg",
                  "source_asset": "mountains.jpg",
                  "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
                  "bytes": 160141,
                  "dimensions": {
                    "originalWidth": 1680,
                    "originalHeight": 1120
                  }
                },
                "type": "description"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": 5,
          "type": "flashcards",
          "variant": "flashcard",
          "style": {
            "background_type": "COLOR",
            "background_color": "#1c1c1c",
            "attached_to_next": false,
            "padding_top": 3,
            "padding_bottom": 3,
            "flashcard_size": "large"
          },
          "cards": [
            {
              "front": {
                "description_html": "<p>Optical and Cableless Interconnects </p>",
                "media": {
                  "path": "resources/images/mountains.jpg",
                  "alt": "mountains.jpg",
                  "source_asset": "mountains.jpg",
                  "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
                  "bytes": 160141,
                  "dimensions": {
                    "originalWidth": 1680,
                    "originalHeight": 1120
                  }
                },
                "type": "description"
              },
              "back": {
                "description_html": "<p style=\"text-align: center\">Next generation scale up networks require extreme data throughput speeds with virtually zero latency latency bottlenecks. Future ORW iterations will seamlessly incorporate direct optical interconnect schemes and cableless backplane configurations, moving massive high density data streams smoothly across neighboring server containers without blocking structural thermal exhaust airways.</p>",
                "media": {
                  "path": "resources/images/mountains.jpg",
                  "alt": "mountains.jpg",
                  "source_asset": "mountains.jpg",
                  "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
                  "bytes": 160141,
                  "dimensions": {
                    "originalWidth": 1680,
                    "originalHeight": 1120
                  }
                },
                "type": "description"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": 6,
          "type": "flashcards",
          "variant": "flashcard",
          "style": {
            "background_type": "COLOR",
            "background_color": "#1c1c1c",
            "attached_to_next": false,
            "padding_top": 3,
            "padding_bottom": 3,
            "flashcard_size": "large"
          },
          "cards": [
            {
              "front": {
                "description_html": "<p>The Logistical Battle: Colocation vs. Purpose-Built Data Centers</p>",
                "media": {
                  "path": "resources/images/mountains.jpg",
                  "alt": "mountains.jpg",
                  "source_asset": "mountains.jpg",
                  "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
                  "bytes": 160141,
                  "dimensions": {
                    "originalWidth": 1680,
                    "originalHeight": 1120
                  }
                },
                "type": "description"
              },
              "back": {
                "description_html": "<p style=\"text-align: center\">Deploying ultra-heavy, high-density, liquid-cooled clusters creates an intense logistical divergence in the industry. Standard commercial colocation facilities must aggressively upgrade their reinforced flooring limits, raised dock infrastructure, and centralized fluid facilities to match the custom, purpose-built concrete and cooling environments constructed by tier one hyperscalers.</p>",
                "media": {
                  "path": "resources/images/mountains.jpg",
                  "alt": "mountains.jpg",
                  "source_asset": "mountains.jpg",
                  "mime_type": "image/jpeg",
                  "bytes": 160141,
                  "dimensions": {
                    "originalWidth": 1680,
                    "originalHeight": 1120
                  }
                },
                "type": "description"
              }
            }
          ]
        },
        {
